507
01:13:55.720 --> 01:14:04.800
Francesco Risitano: So, TLDR, on a high level, the EIP essentially covers the introduction of execution proofs into the protocol.

508
01:14:04.910 --> 01:14:17.560
Francesco Risitano: So an execution proof is essentially a cryptographic proof that allows a validator to, efficiently assert the validity of an execution payload.

509
01:14:18.880 --> 01:14:37.760
Francesco Risitano: So we introduced this cryptographic proof into the protocol with two additional modes. Now, it should be noted that these modes are opt-in. This is a completely optional EIP, so standard validator mechanics are unchanged if they don't opt-in.

510
01:14:37.870 --> 01:14:53.530
Francesco Risitano: The two modes are proof generating mode and, proof verifying mode. So, for the proof generating node, essentially an active validator will kind of enable this mode on their beacon node.

511
01:14:53.590 --> 01:15:12.640
Francesco Risitano: And whenever they receive a block, they validate it via re-execution, and then they will make a request to the proof engine, which I will kind of describe in more detail later, but essentially there's this component called the proof engine, which is responsible for both generating and verifying proofs.

512
01:15:12.640 --> 01:15:26.109
Francesco Risitano: So the active validator will, yeah, request the proofs from the proof engine. There's an external proof node, which, you know, potentially has GPUs and, and other kind of hardware required to generate these proofs.

513
01:15:26.410 --> 01:15:40.090
Francesco Risitano: The proofs will be returned back from the proof node to the proof engine, and subsequently to the, beacon node, essentially the validator, who will sign the proof, and subsequently gossip, the proof on the

514
01:15:40.090 --> 01:15:52.419
Francesco Risitano: on a new execution-proof, gossip topic. Then the second mode is, proof verifying mode. So you've got another node which is… which is opted in to, to verify proofs.

515
01:15:52.520 --> 01:16:09.330
Francesco Risitano: So, this node will essentially receive the proof over the gossip topic, and it will send the proof to the proof engine, which will subsequently, send the proof to the proof node to be verified. And yeah, that's kind of the high-level flow.

516
01:16:09.430 --> 01:16:17.109
Francesco Risitano: we, as I say, this is opt-in, and in addition to the standard, kind of,

517
01:16:17.120 --> 01:16:32.470
Francesco Risitano: duties and, node operations, so we… we still expect that, nodes will do re-execution in addition to these additional modes. Yeah, and I'll dive into the reason for that later.

518
01:16:32.540 --> 01:16:35.920
Francesco Risitano: But just to give some context in regards to the motivation.

519
01:16:36.120 --> 01:16:53.319
Francesco Risitano: The key benefit of this is that, we make payload, validation sublinear and stateless. So, specifically, it's sublinear in the gas limit and the state size. So this has nice properties in regards to the hardware requirements for nodes.

520
01:16:53.490 --> 01:17:12.150
Francesco Risitano: And the implication of this, kind of sublinear relationship is the fact that, payload validity or payload validation is, remains accessible even with, gas limit and, state growth increases, or state increases, state size increases.

521
01:17:12.530 --> 01:17:26.899
Francesco Risitano: In regards to why optional, the technology is still relatively novel. There has been a lot of development and progress over the past few years, but in the first instance, we'd like this to be optional, such that we can kind of

522
01:17:26.960 --> 01:17:38.560
Francesco Risitano: Collect data and, build confidence in the system, make optimizations, etc, before we do, you know, potentially, enshrine this in a future hard fork.

